{"id":"1611.03430","submitter":"Florian Pinsker","authors":"Florian Pinsker","title":"Beyond superfluidity in driven non-equilibrium Bose-Einstein condensates","comments":"Added numerics, typos and small errors are corrected. Text focuses\n  more on the in homogeneously driven effects","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/aa9561","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.quant-gas","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The phenomenon of superfluidity in open Bose-Einstein condensates (BEC) is\nanalysed numerically and analytically. It is found that a superfluid phase is\nfeasible even above the speed of sound, when forces due to inhomogeneous\nnon-equilibrium processes oppose the contributions of homogeneous processes.\nFurthermore a regime of accelerating impurities can be observed for particular\npumping/decay strategies. All findings are derived within the complex\nGross-Pitaevskii (GP) theory with creation and annihilation terms. Utilising\nthis framework the effective force acting on an impurity as it moves with\nvelocity v through the open condensate can be calculated. The result shows that\nthe force is continuously increasing/decreasing with increasing velocity\nstarting from the state of zero motion at v = 0, a property that can be traced\ndown to the additional homogeneous annihilation/creation term in the extended\nGP model. Our findings stand in stark contrast to the concept of a topological\nphase transition to frictionless flow below a critical velocity as observed for\nequilibrium Bose-Einstein condensates analytically, numerically and for trapped\natoms experimentally.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 Nov 2016 18:06:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 23 Nov 2016 18:13:00 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 31 Jan 2017 17:15:30 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 4 Apr 2017 12:13:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-01-17"}
